etymologies: early 16th century; earliest use found in Henry Bradshaw (d. 1513), scholar and hagiographer. From classical Latin praenōminātus, past participle of praenōmināre

early 17th century; earliest use found in William Shakespeare (1564–1616), playwright and poet. From classical Latin praenōmināt-, past participial stem of praenōmināre to name with a praenomen, in post-classical Latin also to name beforehand (early 3rd century in Tertullian), to mention beforehand from prae- + nōmināre

definitions: To name or specify in advance, to mention previously, especially to nominate (a candidate) for an election, post, etc., beforehand. Occasionally without object.

notes.text: Chiefly in U.S. political contexts in later use.
